<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920107-0108</DOCNO><DOCID>920107-0108.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   The Nationalization   Of Nearly Everything</HL><DATE>01/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><NS>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   &quot;Finding a Tonic&quot; for the recession (page one, Dec. 9)will require a course of events. The total debt, made up ofconsumer, corporate, state, federal and international, is soexcessive that we are not going to see any improvement in theeconomy until total debt is reduced enough to motivateexpansion.   The federal debt, approaching $4 trillion, plus about $2trillion in government credit guarantees we do not hearabout, is so heavy that we will see the nationalization ofall thrift institutions, savings and loans, all banks and allcredit unions by the end of this century.</LP><TEXT>   If this conclusion seems too extreme, consider theliquidity of the guarantor.   T.L. Vinyard   Retired Banker   Davenport, Iowa</TEXT></DOC>